1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,140
 - Hello and welcome to our lecture on owned rows in Django.

2
00:00:04,140 --> 00:00:07,120
 So what do I mean by an owned row?

3
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:11,160
 Well up to now, every CRUD application that you've written,

4
00:00:11,160 --> 00:00:14,780
 you got a table, or a model or two,

5
00:00:14,780 --> 00:00:17,280
 maybe they're connected, but basically if you log in,

6
00:00:17,280 --> 00:00:20,500
 you can edit every row, and so if you do a list,

7
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:23,620
 you see an update and delete button on every row.

8
00:00:23,620 --> 00:00:25,480
 Real applications don't work that way.

9
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:28,280
 If you're building a classified ad system,

10
00:00:28,280 --> 00:00:31,320
 some ads belong to you and some ads belong to other people,

11
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:33,520
 you can see them all, but you can't edit them all.

12
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:37,640
 So we have to decide when to put the edit and delete buttons up,

13
00:00:37,640 --> 00:00:40,900
 and only do those for the owner, and we gotta make it

14
00:00:40,900 --> 00:00:43,480
 so you can't sneak in and edit and delete other people's stuff,

15
00:00:43,480 --> 00:00:46,960
 and so we have to protect these rows from being edited

16
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:50,520
 or deleted by anybody but the owner, but anybody can see them.

17
00:00:50,520 --> 00:00:52,600
 And so that's why I call them owned rows.

18
00:00:52,600 --> 00:00:55,080
 If there's a row that you own,

19
00:00:55,080 --> 00:00:57,760
 you will see an edit or delete button.

20
00:00:57,760 --> 00:01:00,440
 If there's a row you don't own, you'll see the row and the data,

21
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:05,100
 and you'll be able to read it and view it, and that's it.

22
00:01:05,100 --> 00:01:07,140
 And so if we go back to how we were working

23
00:01:07,140 --> 00:01:10,560
 in our CRUD application, we were making heavy uses

24
00:01:10,560 --> 00:01:13,600
 of these generic views, the generic list view.

25
00:01:13,600 --> 00:01:16,060
 And so when we're all said and done,

26
00:01:16,060 --> 00:01:20,080
 after a whole bunch of, you know, machinations,

27
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:23,080
 you ended up with a very, very simple view.

28
00:01:23,080 --> 00:01:25,400
 You ended up with a horse list view

29
00:01:25,400 --> 00:01:27,120
 that extended generic list view.

30
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:31,300
 Generic list view is provided to us by Django.

31
00:01:31,300 --> 00:01:34,680
 And the only thing we had to do was take this code,

32
00:01:34,680 --> 00:01:37,000
 which is several thousand lines of code,

33
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,120
 and inform it as to which model we want it to be,

34
00:01:40,120 --> 00:01:41,720
 and then we make another view, right?

35
00:01:41,720 --> 00:01:44,200
 So we make the horse list view

36
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:49,200
 by extending generic list view and informing that list view

37
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:51,800
 that we wanna do this in the model with horses.

38
00:01:51,800 --> 00:01:56,800
 And from that point on, all kinds of convention happens.

39
00:01:56,800 --> 00:01:58,240
 And so we know things like,

40
00:01:58,240 --> 00:01:59,940
 the variable will be named horse list.

41
00:01:59,940 --> 00:02:03,140
 It'll be a list of objects that are retrieved from,

42
00:02:03,140 --> 00:02:05,920
 a list of model objects that are retrieved

43
00:02:05,920 --> 00:02:07,240
 from the database.

44
00:02:07,240 --> 00:02:09,880
 And so we kinda know how that works.

45
00:02:09,880 --> 00:02:14,200
 And it makes things really simple, not a lot of repetition.

46
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:15,960
 Every view kinda looks the same.

47
00:02:15,960 --> 00:02:19,360
 You probably have done cats, dogs, autos,

48
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:20,800
 a couple of different things.

49
00:02:20,800 --> 00:02:23,800
 And they all look very much the same.

50
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:25,880
 And if you get good at it, you should be able

51
00:02:25,880 --> 00:02:27,680
 to make these changes very rapidly.

52
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:30,200
 So if we look at how this is working

53
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:33,140
 kinda from an object-oriented perspective,

54
00:02:33,140 --> 00:02:38,140
 we are making a new class called gView.Views.HorseListView.

55
00:02:38,140 --> 00:02:43,100
 And we are extending, our parent class

56
00:02:43,100 --> 00:02:44,780
 is the generic list view.

57
00:02:44,780 --> 00:02:48,680
 And we're sort of adding our own little special sauce

58
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:53,240
 by saying one class variable model equals horse.

59
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:55,840
 Okay, and so that's kinda what's going on here.

60
00:02:55,840 --> 00:03:00,700
 Now, in this owner view,

61
00:03:00,700 --> 00:03:03,240
 we're going to do something quite similar.

62
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:05,680
 And that is, when we're going to have an article,

63
00:03:05,680 --> 00:03:10,440
 and this is all from the DJ Free Samples My Arts example,

64
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:13,360
 we're going to extend owner list view.

65
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:15,640
 Now, if we were, and soon we will look inside

66
00:03:15,640 --> 00:03:17,880
 owner list view and we will see that owner list view

67
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:21,380
 is extending generic list view.

68
00:03:21,380 --> 00:03:26,380
 And we're, this model equals article

69
00:03:26,380 --> 00:03:28,880
 is informing owner list view.

70
00:03:28,880 --> 00:03:31,240
 The difference is, this is our code.

71
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:32,680
 That belongs to us.

72
00:03:32,680 --> 00:03:34,960
 And in the last part, we will show you everything

73
00:03:34,960 --> 00:03:37,160
 that you have to do to build one of these things.

74
00:03:37,160 --> 00:03:39,140
 And so we're taking the list view,

75
00:03:39,140 --> 00:03:41,600
 which has almost everything we want,

76
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:43,520
 and we're going to add one feature to it.

77
00:03:43,520 --> 00:03:45,200
 And then we're going to extend the list view

78
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:48,140
 and create a new view called owner list view.

79
00:03:48,140 --> 00:03:51,560
 Or you might call it list view for owned rows.

80
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:55,680
 And at that point, you just, you're good.

81
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:58,400
 And this has, this class owner list view,

82
00:03:58,400 --> 00:03:59,700
 which we'll see in a second,

83
00:03:59,700 --> 00:04:03,800
 has everything you need to deal with rows that are owned.

84
00:04:03,800 --> 00:04:08,800
 And for example, we're going to have a owner column.

85
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:11,600
 So every article is going to have an owner.

86
00:04:11,600 --> 00:04:13,960
 And if that's equal to the current logged in user,

87
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:17,760
 then we're going to show these little edit and delete buttons.

88
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:19,240
 But if the article owner,

89
00:04:19,240 --> 00:04:23,700
 the owner value inside the article object, or the model,

90
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:26,760
 if that owner is not equal to the current user,

91
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:27,820
 we don't show it.

92
00:04:27,820 --> 00:04:30,240
 Now, not showing a link does not mean

93
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:31,600
 you've protected it from editing.

94
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:35,720
 We'll show you later how that protection from editing happens.

95
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:38,080
 But this is such a common problem

96
00:04:38,080 --> 00:04:40,340
 that we want to just be able to, in a sense,

97
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:42,340
 say look, here's a list view.

98
00:04:42,340 --> 00:04:44,720
 Here's a list view with this special owner column in it,

99
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:46,880
 and we want to maintain the owner column.

100
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:49,500
 We don't want to have to write hundreds of lines of code

101
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:52,160
 in every view that we want to have this owner column.

102
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:55,880
 So we just use object-oriented techniques to accomplish this.

103
00:04:55,880 --> 00:04:57,720
 And so we're going to use inheritance.

104
00:04:57,720 --> 00:05:00,560
 And we talked about it and we'll talk about it again.

105
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:03,680
 Inheritance is the idea that you have a class,

106
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:05,080
 you're going to make another class

107
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:07,880
 that inherits all of its, all that parent class,

108
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:11,180
 and then extends it, adds a little bit of stuff to it.

109
00:05:11,180 --> 00:05:13,760
 And it's another form of don't repeat yourself.

110
00:05:13,760 --> 00:05:17,000
 Do something once in a parent class.

111
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,240
 You make the parent class sometimes quite generic.

112
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:22,800
 Then you make a child class that extends the parent class.

113
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:24,480
 And then we use the child class.

114
00:05:24,480 --> 00:05:28,020
 Or we could call them subclasses or child classes.

115
00:05:28,020 --> 00:05:29,680
 There's a whole bunch of different terminology

116
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:31,200
 and it's all pretty much equivalent.

117
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:34,340
 Subclasses are more specialized versions of a class.

118
00:05:34,340 --> 00:05:36,440
 They inherit attributes and methods

119
00:05:36,440 --> 00:05:39,640
 from their parent classes and can introduce their own.

120
00:05:39,640 --> 00:05:43,780
 Again, basic object-oriented programming.

121
00:05:43,780 --> 00:05:45,740
 So up next we're going to talk a little bit

122
00:05:45,740 --> 00:05:47,800
 about how it is that we can peek in

123
00:05:47,800 --> 00:05:49,720
 to one of these generic views

124
00:05:49,720 --> 00:05:51,800
 and add our own special sauce for it.

125
00:05:51,800 --> 00:05:54,380
 (upbeat music)

